// Content Sprint 9: Cancellations, Returns and Refunds.
window.CONTENT_SPRINT_9 = {"refund-foundations":{"summary":"Understand how Marketplacer coordinates cancellation and return workflows, where customer funds are actually refunded, and how pre-dispatch and post-dispatch scenarios differ.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Finance","Seller management","Technology"],"sections":{"Marketplacer Workflow":"<p>Marketplacer uses a <strong>Refund Request</strong> to manage both a cancellation before dispatch and a return or refund after dispatch.</p>\n<p>The Refund Request records the affected Line Items, quantities, reasons, notes, attachments, Seller decisions, Operator actions and workflow status. A completed refund creates an adjustment to the original Seller Invoice through an <strong>Invoice Amendment</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\">\n<div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>A refund requirement is identified</strong><p>The customer, Seller or Operator identifies a cancellation or return requirement.</p></div></div>\n<div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>A Refund Request is created</strong><p>The correct Seller Invoice, Line Items, quantities and reason are recorded.</p></div></div>\n<div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>The required workflow actions are completed</strong><p>The Seller or Operator accepts, denies or requires a physical return.</p></div></div>\n<div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>The Operator finalises the financial outcome</strong><p>The customer refund and Seller remittance effects are reviewed.</p></div></div>\n<div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>The marketplace records are reconciled</strong><p>The Invoice Amendment, payment refund and Seller remittance must agree.</p></div></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Completing the workflow in Marketplacer and returning money to the customer are related but separate responsibilities.</strong> Marketplacer records the operational and financial workflow. The marketplace's payment provider or connected payment system returns the funds to the customer.</div>\n<p>Some integrations connect these steps. For example, an approved Marketplacer refund can trigger a customer refund in a connected Shopify Plus implementation. Other marketplaces require Customer Service or Finance to process the payment manually.</p>","Customer Request Channels":"<p>Marketplacer does not determine how the customer first asks for a cancellation or return. The Operator may provide a customer account, returns portal, support form, email, phone, live chat or another approved request channel.</p>\n<p>The customer request must then enter the Marketplacer workflow through one of the supported paths:</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Marketplacer entry point</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Operator Portal</strong></td><td>Customer Service or marketplace operations creates the request.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Seller Portal</strong></td><td>The Seller cancels or initiates a refund where the relevant permission is enabled.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Operator or Seller API</strong></td><td>A connected storefront, returns platform or Seller system creates the request.</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Connect the customer request channel to Marketplacer intentionally.</strong> A return recorded only in a storefront, customer service platform or Seller system does not update Marketplacer unless an integration or operational process creates the corresponding Refund Request.</div>\n<p>Define where requests are submitted, who validates eligibility, who creates the Marketplacer record, how evidence is transferred, who communicates the outcome and how duplicate requests are prevented.</p>","Payment Gateway Responsibilities":"<p>Marketplacer and the customer payment system perform different parts of the refund process.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Marketplacer</th><th>Payment gateway or connected payment system</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Records the Refund Request</td><td>Returns funds to the customer</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Tracks Seller and Operator actions</td><td>Updates the payment transaction</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Records accepted and denied Line Items</td><td>Records whether the monetary refund succeeded or failed</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Calculates marketplace adjustments</td><td>Handles settlement and payment-method limitations</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Creates Invoice Amendments</td><td>Provides the payment refund reference</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Adjusts Seller remittance</td><td>Supports cash reconciliation</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Do not assume that selecting <strong>Mark as Refunded</strong> has moved customer funds unless the marketplace's payment integration has been designed and tested to do so.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><div class=\"structure-node\">Customer refund amount</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Payment transaction</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Storefront Order</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Marketplacer Refund Request</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Invoice Amendment</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Seller remittance</div></div>","Cancellation vs Return":"<p>Marketplacer uses the same Refund Request framework for two business scenarios.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Refund flow</th><th>When it applies</th><th>Physical return</th><th>Common examples</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Cancellation</strong></td><td>Before the affected item or quantity is dispatched</td><td>No</td><td>Customer changes their mind, accidental purchase, Seller out of stock</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Return or returnless refund</strong></td><td>After the affected item or quantity is dispatched</td><td>Required or not required</td><td>Damaged item, incorrect item, faulty product, post-delivery change of mind</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p><strong>In Marketplacer, a cancellation applies before dispatch, while a return applies after dispatch.</strong></p>\n<h3>Cancellation</h3><p>A cancellation resolves an item that has not been shipped. No physical return is required. A standard cancellation moves directly to <strong>Processed</strong>, ready for Operator finalisation.</p>\n<h3>Post-dispatch return or refund</h3><p>A post-dispatch request usually begins as <strong>Awaiting</strong>. The Seller or Operator may deny it, approve a returnless refund, or require the item to be returned and assessed.</p>","Pre-Dispatch vs Post-Dispatch":"<p>The dispatch state of the affected Line Item quantity determines which workflow applies.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Affected quantity</th><th>Correct workflow</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Has not been dispatched</td><td>Pre-dispatch cancellation</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Has already been dispatched</td><td>Post-dispatch return or returnless refund</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Some units dispatched and some outstanding</td><td>Use the appropriate workflow for each quantity</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3>Pre-dispatch flow</h3>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Cancellation created</strong><p>The item or quantity is still undispatched.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Status becomes Processed</strong><p>No Seller approval or physical return is required.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Operator finalises</strong><p>The financial outcome and payment refund are completed.</p></div></div></div>\n<h3>Post-dispatch flow</h3>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Return request created</strong><p>The item has already been dispatched.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Status remains Awaiting</strong><p>A decision or physical return is still required.</p></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Accepted items become Processed</strong><p>The Operator then finalises the financial outcome.</p></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Review the specific Line Item quantity.</strong> A partially fulfilled Seller Invoice can contain both cancellation and return workflows.</div>","Refund Requests and Invoice Amendments":"<p>A <strong>Refund Request</strong> manages the decisions and actions required to resolve the cancellation or return. An <strong>Invoice Amendment</strong> records the resulting financial adjustment to the Seller Invoice.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><div class=\"structure-node\"><strong>Refund Request</strong><br>Workflow, decisions and approval</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↓</div><div class=\"structure-node\"><strong>Invoice Amendment</strong><br>Financial adjustment</div></div>\n<p>An Invoice Amendment can include refunded item value, refunded postage, commission adjustment, merchant fee adjustment, tax and other approved financial changes. It also determines the amount to recover from or return to the Seller through remittance.</p>\n<p>Where credit notes are enabled, the amendment can generate a Seller credit note and a commission credit note.</p>","Roles and Ownership":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Role</th><th>Typical responsibility</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Customer</strong></td><td>Submits the request and supplies evidence where required.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Customer Service</strong></td><td>Confirms the issue, explains policy and creates or routes the request.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Seller</strong></td><td>Cancels undispatched items where permitted, reviews post-dispatch requests and assesses returned items.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Marketplace Operations</strong></td><td>Monitors requests, resolves exceptions and finalises the Marketplacer workflow.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Finance or Payments</strong></td><td>Confirms the actual customer refund and reconciles the payment transaction.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Technology or Integration Team</strong></td><td>Connects request channels, statuses and payment actions to Marketplacer.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Seller Management</strong></td><td>Ensures Sellers understand permissions, policy and response expectations.</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>The Operator remains accountable for ensuring that the customer, Seller and financial outcomes are consistent, even when individual actions are delegated.</p>","Marketplace Policy Decisions":"<p>Decide the operating position before configuring Refund Reasons and Seller permissions.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Questions to answer</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Customer cancellation</td><td>Can customers request cancellation before dispatch?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Request channel</td><td>Where will customers submit cancellations and returns?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Policy model</td><td>Will the marketplace use one policy or Seller-specific policies?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Seller authority</td><td>Can Sellers initiate cancellations and post-dispatch refunds?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Return decision</td><td>Who decides whether the item must be returned?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Return shipping</td><td>Who supplies instructions or labels, and who pays?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Returnless refunds</td><td>When may the customer keep or dispose of the item?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Financial treatment</td><td>Which item, postage, commission and merchant-fee amounts are reversed or retained?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Customer payment</td><td>Is the cash refund manual or automated?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Disputes</td><td>Who makes the final decision when the Operator and Seller disagree?</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Reflect the approved decisions consistently in customer terms, Seller agreements, onboarding materials, Marketplacer configuration, payment design and test scenarios.</p>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>Cancellation and return policies are approved</li><li>The customer request channel is defined</li><li>Pre-dispatch, post-dispatch and denial reasons are configured</li><li>Seller cancellation and refund permissions are intentional</li><li>Customer Service can create the correct Refund Request</li><li>Sellers understand Return and Do Not Return</li><li>Return shipping ownership is documented</li><li>The Operator finalisation owner is named</li><li>The payment refund process is documented and tested</li><li>Invoice Amendments and remittance effects are understood</li><li>Finance can reconcile Marketplacer and payment records</li><li>Pre-dispatch, returnless, return-required, denied and partial outcomes are tested</li><li>Unresolved requests are monitored</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360040011851-Enable-and-use-the-returns-module\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Enable and use the returns module</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24105251849229-Returns-FAQs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Returns FAQs</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/8838370021773-Cancel-an-order-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Cancel an order as a Seller</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/13278067225741-Action-a-refund-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Action a refund as a Seller</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360050107431-Refund-recovery\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Refund recovery</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/refunds/howto_advancedrefund/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to use the refunds flow</a></li>\n</ul>"},"related":[["order-refund-decisions","Order, Cancellation and Refund Decisions"],["order-exceptions","Order Exceptions"],["payments","Payments"],["remittances","Remittances"],["additional-charges","Additional Charges Invoices"]]},"refund-configuration":{"summary":"Configure the Refund Reasons, Seller permissions, return documents and notifications that control how cancellations and post-dispatch refunds are handled across the marketplace.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Seller management","Finance","Technology"],"sections":{"Confirm the Refund Framework":"<p>Before configuring reasons or Seller permissions, confirm that the marketplace uses the current advanced refund workflow.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Configuration → Seller Settings</strong> and review <strong>Enable advanced refunds</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Plan the change before enabling it.</strong> Once advanced refunds are enabled, all Seller refunds use the advanced workflow and the setting cannot be disabled. Confirm that policy, payment processing, Seller training and integrations are ready.</div>\n<p>Production and Sandbox should reflect the same intended refund configuration before end-to-end testing begins.</p>","Configure Refund Reasons":"<p>Go to <strong>Configuration → Refund Reasons</strong>.</p>\n<p>Create reasons in three groups:</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Refund Reason group</th><th>When it is used</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Pre-Dispatch Refund Reasons</strong></td><td>The affected quantity has not been dispatched.</td><td>Customer cancelled, Seller out of stock, Unable to fulfil</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Post-Dispatch Refund Reasons</strong></td><td>The affected quantity has already been dispatched.</td><td>Incorrect item, Damaged item, Faulty product, Change of mind</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Deny Refund Reasons</strong></td><td>A request or returned item is rejected.</td><td>Outside return period, Does not meet policy, Insufficient evidence</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Pre-dispatch and post-dispatch reasons should be unique. The selected reason should make the workflow clear in reporting and investigations.</p>\n<h3>Example reason library</h3>\n<div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Pre-dispatch</h3><p>Customer requested cancellation, Duplicate order, Seller out of stock, Product unavailable, Seller unable to fulfil.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Post-dispatch</h3><p>Incorrect item received, Item damaged, Product faulty, Missing parts, Product not as described, Change of mind.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Denied</h3><p>Outside return period, Product not eligible, Returned condition unacceptable, No fault identified, Insufficient evidence.</p></article></div>","Design Clear and Useful Reasons":"<p>A good Refund Reason is easy to understand, specific enough for reporting, aligned with customer policy, distinct from other reasons and appropriate for the workflow where it appears.</p>\n<p>Avoid vague options such as <em>Issue</em>, <em>Cancelled</em> or <em>Problem with item</em>. Where <strong>Other</strong> is genuinely required, require explanatory notes.</p>\n<p>Use the smallest set that still separates meaningful causes. A long list creates inconsistent selection and poor reporting.</p>\n<div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Design for action as well as reporting.</strong> Reasons such as Seller out of stock, damaged item and change of mind support different Seller-performance and customer-service responses.</div>","Configure Seller Permissions":"<p>Seller refund permissions are configured individually.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Sellers → Manage Sellers → Edit Seller</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Setting</th><th>What it controls</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><strong>Allow order cancellations?</strong></td><td>Allows the Seller to cancel an undispatched item or quantity.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Allow Sellers to initiate refunds?</strong></td><td>Allows the Seller to start a post-dispatch Refund Request.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Return label enabled</strong></td><td>Controls whether the generated return form includes the Seller return-address label.</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<h3>Allow order cancellations</h3><p>Enable this when the Seller should be able to report an undispatched fulfilment failure directly. The Seller can cancel a Paid, but not Sent, Order and the request moves to Processed for Operator finalisation.</p>\n<h3>Allow Sellers to initiate refunds</h3><p>Enable this when customers may contact the Seller directly, return an item to a Seller location, or a connected Seller system creates Refund Requests.</p>\n<p>Create a standard marketplace position, then document Seller-specific exceptions. The Seller agreement and onboarding materials should match the configured permissions.</p>","Understand the Return Label":"<p><strong>Return label enabled</strong> controls whether the generated return form includes a label containing the Seller's return address.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>The standard Marketplacer return label is not a prepaid courier label.</strong> It supplies the return address only.</div>\n<p>The marketplace must separately decide who pays return shipping, who creates a prepaid Carrier label, whether the customer arranges postage, which address is used and who communicates the instructions.</p>\n<p>Confirm that the Seller return-address information is accurate before enabling the label.</p>","Configure Refund Notifications":"<p>Marketplacer can send refund-related notifications to Sellers as the workflow progresses.</p>\n<p>Where another system owns Seller notifications, review <strong>Configuration → Seller Settings → Skip sending refund emails to Sellers</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Suppress Marketplacer emails only when a reliable replacement exists.</strong> The external process should cover new requests, Seller decisions, expected returns, returned-item assessment, denials and integration failures.</div>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Notification</th><th>Possible sending system</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>New customer return request</td><td>Customer service platform or Marketplacer</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Seller decision required</td><td>Marketplacer or connected Seller system</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Return instructions</td><td>Storefront or returns platform</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Refund approved</td><td>Customer service or storefront</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Customer funds returned</td><td>Payment or storefront system</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Test Sandbox carefully so messages do not reach live Sellers or customers.</p>","Align Connected Seller Workflows":"<p>A Seller may work through the Seller Portal, Shopify through MConnect, another ecommerce or order-management system, the Seller GraphQL API or an Operator-managed process.</p>\n<p>For each connected Seller, confirm:</p><ol><li>Where cancellation or refund is initiated.</li><li>Whether Marketplacer receives it automatically.</li><li>Where the Seller makes the return or returnless decision.</li><li>Where the returned item is assessed.</li><li>Which system sends customer communications.</li><li>How duplicate requests are prevented.</li><li>How failures are monitored.</li></ol>\n<p>A request created only in an external system does not update Marketplacer unless the integration creates the corresponding Refund Request.</p>","Configuration Governance":"<p>Record the approved refund configuration in a shared decision log.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Configuration item</th><th>Approved decision</th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td>Advanced refunds</td><td>Enabled or already active</td></tr><tr><td>Pre-dispatch reasons</td><td>Approved list</td></tr><tr><td>Post-dispatch reasons</td><td>Approved list</td></tr><tr><td>Deny reasons</td><td>Approved list</td></tr><tr><td>Seller cancellation permission</td><td>Default and exceptions</td></tr><tr><td>Seller refund-initiation permission</td><td>Default and exceptions</td></tr><tr><td>Return postage owner</td><td>Operator, Seller or customer</td></tr><tr><td>Seller refund emails</td><td>Marketplacer or external system</td></tr><tr><td>Customer payment execution</td><td>Manual or automated</td></tr><tr><td>Finalisation and monitoring owners</td><td>Named teams</td></tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n<p>Review the register when customer policy, Seller terms, integrations or operating models change.</p>","Test the Configuration":"<h3>Refund Reasons</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>All approved reason groups appear</li><li>Pre-dispatch and post-dispatch wording is not duplicated</li><li>Reporting shows the selected reason clearly</li></ul>\n<h3>Seller permissions</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller with cancellation permission can cancel an undispatched item</li><li>Seller without permission cannot access the action</li><li>Seller with refund-initiation permission can start a post-dispatch request</li><li>Operator can still create the required requests</li></ul>\n<h3>Return label and notifications</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Generated return form shows the correct address</li><li>The address label is not presented as prepaid postage</li><li>Duplicate notifications are prevented</li><li>Sandbox messages do not reach live recipients</li></ul>\n<h3>Connected workflows</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>One Marketplacer Refund Request is created</li><li>Reasons and notes transfer correctly</li><li>Seller and Operator actions synchronise</li><li>Retries do not create duplicates</li></ul>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Advanced refunds are active or approved for activation</li><li>All three Refund Reason groups are configured</li><li>Reasons are clear and suitable for reporting</li><li>Seller permissions are configured intentionally</li><li>Seller-specific exceptions are documented</li><li>Return addresses are accurate</li><li>Teams understand the standard label is not prepaid</li><li>Return-postage and notification ownership are defined</li><li>Connected workflows are tested</li><li>Customer Service and Sellers have received guidance</li><li>Configuration decisions are recorded and owned</li></ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360040011851-Enable-and-use-the-returns-module\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Enable and use the returns module</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/25930591592973-Seller-settings\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Seller settings</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/8838370021773-Cancel-an-order-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Cancel an order as a Seller</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24105251849229-Returns-FAQs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Returns FAQs</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/28414815410445-Shopify-Plus-How-data-is-synchronized\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Shopify Plus: How data is synchronized</a></li>\n</ul>"},"related":[["refund-foundations","Refund Foundations"],["order-refund-decisions","Order, Cancellation and Refund Decisions"],["default-seller-configuration","Default Seller Configuration"],["order-exceptions","Order Exceptions"],["integration-architecture","Integration Architecture"]]},"cancellation-workflow":{"summary":"Process pre-dispatch cancellations consistently, whether initiated by the Operator or Seller, and ensure the Marketplacer record, customer refund and Seller remittance reconcile.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Seller management","Finance","Technology"],"sections":{"When to Use the Cancellation Workflow":"<p>Use a cancellation when the affected item or quantity <strong>has not been dispatched</strong>.</p>\n<p>Common reasons include customer change of mind, accidental order, Seller out of stock, damaged warehouse stock, delivery restrictions, listing error or fraud and compliance concerns.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Undispatched quantity identified</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Cancellation created</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Status becomes Processed</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Operator finalises and refunds the customer</strong></div></div></div>\n<p>A cancellation can apply to the complete Seller Invoice, selected Line Items or part of a Line Item quantity.</p>","Confirm Cancellation Eligibility":"<p>Confirm the fulfilment state of the specific quantity being cancelled.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Fulfilment state</th><th>Correct workflow</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Not dispatched</td><td>Cancellation</td></tr><tr><td>Already dispatched</td><td>Post-dispatch return or returnless refund</td></tr><tr><td>Some units dispatched and some outstanding</td><td>Cancel only the outstanding units</td></tr><tr><td>Marked as dispatched incorrectly</td><td>Investigate the Shipment and use the correct exception process</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>The Seller Portal allows a permitted Seller to use <strong>Cancel Order</strong> for an Order with a <strong>Paid</strong>, but not <strong>Sent</strong>, status.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Dispatch must reflect the physical fulfilment event.</strong> Do not dispatch an unavailable item to close the Invoice, cancel an item that has physically left the warehouse or create parallel cancellations in several systems.</div>","Operator-Initiated Cancellation":"<p>An authorised Operator user can create a cancellation without requiring the Seller cancellation permission.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Orders → Start a Refund Request</strong>.</p><ol><li>Search for the correct Seller Invoice.</li><li>Select <strong>Start a Refund Request</strong>.</li><li>Select <strong>Cancellation</strong>.</li><li>Select the affected Line Items and quantities.</li><li>Choose the pre-dispatch Refund Reason.</li><li>Add notes or evidence where required.</li><li>Create the Refund Request.</li></ol>\n<p>The request moves directly to <strong>Processed</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Example</h3><p>A customer wants to cancel a coffee machine but keep two packs of coffee pods. Select only the coffee machine quantity. The pods remain available for fulfilment.</p>","Seller-Initiated Cancellation":"<p>A Seller can initiate a cancellation only when <strong>Allow order cancellations?</strong> is enabled.</p>\n<p>In the Seller Portal, go to <strong>Orders → All Orders</strong>.</p><ol><li>Find the Paid, but not Sent, Order.</li><li>Open the three-dot menu.</li><li>Select <strong>Cancel Order</strong>.</li><li>Select the affected items and quantities.</li><li>Choose the cancellation reason.</li><li>Add notes.</li><li>Select <strong>Create Refund</strong>.</li></ol>\n<p>The Refund Request appears as <strong>Processed</strong>. The Seller does not need to approve it again. The next action belongs to the Operator.</p>\n<p>Where permission is disabled, the Seller should provide the Invoice number, affected quantity, reason, dispatch state and evidence through the agreed escalation channel.</p>","Processed Status":"<p>A pre-dispatch cancellation skips <strong>Awaiting</strong> and moves directly to <strong>Processed</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Initiator</th><th>Permission required</th><th>Initial status</th><th>Next action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Operator</td><td>No Seller permission</td><td>Processed</td><td>Operator processes refund</td></tr><tr><td>Seller</td><td>Allow order cancellations?</td><td>Processed</td><td>Operator processes refund</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Processed means ready for Operator financial finalisation.</strong> It does not confirm that customer funds have moved or that the payment gateway refund succeeded.</div>","Operator Finalisation":"<p>Go to <strong>Orders → Refund Requests</strong>, filter for <strong>Processed</strong>, open the request and select <strong>Process Refund</strong>.</p>\n<p>Confirm the correct Seller Invoice, Line Items, quantities, reason, dispatch state and that no duplicate request exists.</p>\n<p>Review item value, postage, tax, commission, merchant fees, Operator-funded or Seller-funded amounts and the Seller remittance effect. Then select <strong>Mark as Refunded</strong>.</p>\n<p>Marketplacer creates the Invoice Amendment and changes the request to Refunded.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Review the financial values against the original checkout and payment record.</strong> Do not finalise from status alone.</div>","Customer Refund":"<p>Return the customer's funds through the marketplace's approved payment process.</p>\n<p>The refund may be manual in the payment gateway, triggered automatically after Marketplacer approval, processed through the storefront or handled by another connected platform.</p>\n<p>Record the payment refund reference and confirm the customer communication explains the cancelled item, refund amount, postage treatment, expected payment timing and any items that will still be fulfilled.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Marketplacer completion does not independently move funds.</strong> Confirm the payment response unless an automated integration has been tested end to end.</div>","Partial Cancellations":"<h3>Selected Line Items</h3><p>Cancel only the affected item while the remaining Line Items continue through fulfilment.</p>\n<h3>Part of a quantity</h3><div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><tbody><tr><th>Quantity ordered</th><td>3</td></tr><tr><th>Quantity available</th><td>2</td></tr><tr><th>Quantity cancelled</th><td>1</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Confirm that the cancelled quantity is not in a Shipment, the remaining quantity can still be dispatched, the storefront reflects the partial refund and remittance includes only payable amounts.</p>\n<h3>Multi-Seller Orders</h3><p>A cancellation against one Seller Invoice must not affect another Seller's Invoice. Customer communication should explain that the rest of the Order is still proceeding.</p>","Connected and API Workflows":"<p>A connected storefront, returns platform or Seller system can create a cancellation through GraphQL.</p>\n<p>Use <code>refundRequestCreate</code> with the correct Invoice ID, Line Item ID, quantity, reason and notes. A cancellation that requires no Seller decision uses the Line Item creation status <code>REFUND_ACCEPTED</code>.</p>\n<p>The integration should confirm that the quantity is undispatched, prevent duplicates, store Marketplacer IDs, monitor GraphQL errors, synchronise the outcome and coordinate the payment refund.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Define one source of truth for cancellation initiation.</strong> Do not assume cancelling in an external platform automatically creates a Marketplacer Refund Request.</div>","Monitoring and Exceptions":"<p>Monitor Seller cancellations awaiting finalisation, aged Processed requests, duplicate requests, failed payment refunds, mismatched amounts, items cancelled after physical dispatch, cancelled quantities still included in Shipments and remittance discrepancies.</p>\n<h3>Seller cancels because stock is unavailable</h3><p>Resolve the customer cancellation, then investigate stock synchronisation, buffers, overselling, Seller process and recurring cancellation rates.</p>\n<h3>Item is dispatched after cancellation</h3><ol><li>Confirm when physical dispatch occurred.</li><li>Prevent a duplicate payment refund.</li><li>Contact the customer and Seller.</li><li>Attempt interception where possible.</li><li>Move the case into the agreed return process if the customer receives the item.</li><li>Reconcile the existing request, payment and remittance records.</li></ol>","Test the Cancellation Workflow":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Operator cancels a complete undispatched Invoice</li><li>Operator cancels one Line Item</li><li>Operator cancels part of a multi-quantity Line Item</li><li>Seller cancels with permission enabled</li><li>Seller cannot cancel with permission disabled</li><li>Request moves directly to Processed</li><li>Seller has no further action after creation</li><li>Operator marks the request as Refunded</li><li>Invoice Amendment and remittance adjustment are correct</li><li>Payment refund is completed and recorded</li><li>One Seller is cancelled while another Seller continues</li><li>Duplicate cancellation is prevented</li><li>API cancellation uses REFUND_ACCEPTED</li></ul>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Pre-dispatch reasons are configured</li><li>The customer cancellation channel is documented</li><li>Seller cancellation permissions are intentional</li><li>Sellers know when to use Cancel Order</li><li>Customer Service can locate the correct Seller Invoice</li><li>Partial and multi-Seller cancellations are tested</li><li>Processed requests have a monitoring owner</li><li>Commission, merchant fee and postage treatment is documented</li><li>The payment refund process is tested</li><li>Payment references are retained</li><li>Storefront and remittance reconciliation is tested</li><li>Out-of-stock cancellations feed into Seller performance management</li></ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/8838370021773-Cancel-an-order-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Cancel an order as a Seller</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360040011851-Enable-and-use-the-returns-module\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Enable and use the returns module</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24105251849229-Returns-FAQs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Returns FAQs</a></li><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/refunds/howto_advancedrefund/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to use the refunds flow</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360050107431-Refund-recovery\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Refund recovery</a></li></ul>"},"related":[["refund-foundations","Refund Foundations"],["refund-configuration","Refund Configuration"],["return-workflow","Return Workflow"],["refund-statuses","Refund Statuses"],["refund-financial-adjustments","Refund Financial Adjustments"]]},"return-workflow":{"summary":"Manage post-dispatch Refund Requests from initiation through the Seller decision, physical return where required, returned-item assessment, Operator finalisation and customer refund.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Seller management","Finance","Technology"],"sections":{"When to Use the Return Workflow":"<p>Use the post-dispatch workflow when the affected item or quantity <strong>has already been dispatched</strong>.</p>\n<p>Common reasons include incorrect item, damage, fault, missing parts, product not as described, change of mind, reported non-delivery or another eligible post-delivery issue.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><div class=\"structure-node\"><strong>Post-dispatch Refund Request</strong></div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↓</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Returnless refund<br>Customer keeps or disposes of the item</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">or</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Return required<br>Item is returned and assessed</div></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Do not cancel an item that has already been dispatched.</strong> Use the post-dispatch Refund Request workflow.</div>","How a Post-Dispatch Request Starts":"<p>A post-dispatch Refund Request can be initiated by an Operator, an authorised Seller or a connected storefront, returns platform or customer service system through GraphQL.</p>\n<h3>Operator-initiated request</h3><p>Go to <strong>Orders → Start a Refund Request</strong>, select the Seller Invoice, choose <strong>Return</strong>, select Line Items and quantities, choose the post-dispatch reason, add evidence and create the request.</p>\n<h3>Seller-initiated request</h3><p>Where <strong>Allow Sellers to initiate refunds?</strong> is enabled, the Seller goes to <strong>Orders → All Orders</strong>, selects <strong>Initiate Refund</strong>, chooses the affected items, reason and notes, then saves the request.</p>\n<p>The request begins in <strong>Awaiting</strong> because a decision or return-processing step remains.</p>","Awaiting Status and Action Ownership":"<p><strong>Awaiting</strong> can mean that the Seller still needs to accept or deny the request, a physical return is expected, the returned item is waiting for assessment, or the Operator can process or deny the eligible return.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Seller action</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Action Refund</strong></td><td>Decide whether to deny, approve without return or require a return.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Action Return</strong></td><td>Assess the item after it has been returned.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>In the Operator Portal, use the request status and available action together. A greyed-out action can indicate that the Seller must complete the current step first.</p>","Seller Decision":"<p>When <strong>Action Refund</strong> is available, the Seller decides each affected Line Item separately.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Deny Refund</strong></td><td>The selected Line Item is rejected.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Accept Refund → Do Not Return</strong></td><td>The refund proceeds without a physical return.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Accept Refund → Return</strong></td><td>The item must be returned before final approval.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Different Line Items in the same Refund Request can receive different outcomes. Sellers should add clear notes and evidence.</p>","Returnless Refund":"<p>Use <strong>Do Not Return</strong> when the refund can proceed without the customer sending the item back.</p>\n<p>Examples include destroyed or unsafe items, low-value items where return cost is disproportionate, sufficient photographic evidence or an approved marketplace policy.</p>\n<p>In <strong>Orders → All Refund Requests → Action Refund</strong>, the Seller selects the items, chooses <strong>Accept Refund → Do Not Return</strong>, adds notes and evidence, then selects <strong>Approve Refund</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Status: Awaiting</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Seller approves Do Not Return</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Status: Processed</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Operator finalises</strong></div></div></div>","Return Required":"<p>Use <strong>Return</strong> when the Seller or Operator must receive and inspect the item before approving the refund.</p>\n<p>In <strong>Action Refund</strong>, the Seller selects the items, chooses <strong>Accept Refund → Return</strong>, records Carrier, tracking number, drop-off URL, notes and attachments, then selects <strong>Approve Return</strong>.</p>\n<p>The request remains <strong>Awaiting</strong> while the item is in the return process.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Return required</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Customer sends item</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Seller receives and assesses</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Seller accepts or denies</strong></div></div></div>","Return Shipping and Customer Instructions":"<p>Define who creates the return Shipment, who pays postage, whether a prepaid Carrier label is supplied, which address is used, how tracking is communicated and what happens when the customer does not return the item.</p>\n<p>Marketplacer stores Carrier, tracking, drop-off URL, notes and attachments, but the Operator's storefront, returns platform or Customer Service process must ensure that the customer receives the instructions.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Do not assume that entering a return label or tracking information in Marketplacer has notified the customer.</strong></div>\n<p>The customer should receive the return address, method, deadline, packaging requirements, postage arrangements, tracking process and instructions to retain proof of postage.</p>","Assess the Returned Item":"<p>When the Seller receives the item, the request appears with <strong>Action Return</strong>.</p>\n<p>The Seller reviews the correct item, quantity, product condition, accessories, packaging, signs of use, return timing and the evidence supporting the reason.</p>\n<h3>Accept the returned item</h3><p>Select <strong>Accept Return → Approve Return</strong>. When no further items require action, the request becomes <strong>Processed</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Deny the returned item</h3><p>Select <strong>Deny Return</strong>, choose the Deny Refund Reason and add notes and evidence. The Operator must ensure that the customer is informed and that any dispute follows the marketplace policy.</p>\n<p>An Operator can also deny an eligible Awaiting return from <strong>Orders → Refund Requests → Process Return → Deny Refund</strong>.</p>","Operator Finalisation":"<p>When accepted items are <strong>Processed</strong>, go to <strong>Orders → Refund Requests</strong>, select <strong>Process Refund</strong>, review items, quantities, postage, commission, merchant fees and remittance, then select <strong>Mark as Refunded</strong>.</p>\n<p>Marketplacer creates the Invoice Amendment. The customer payment must also be completed through the payment gateway or connected workflow.</p>","Partial and Mixed Outcomes":"<p>One Refund Request can contain returnless, return-required and denied Line Items.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Line Item</th><th>Outcome</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Damaged vase</td><td>Returnless refund accepted</td></tr><tr><td>Unwanted cushion</td><td>Return required</td></tr><tr><td>Used bedding</td><td>Denied</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>The request remains Awaiting while any item is Pending Approval or Awaiting Return. If all accepted items are ready, it becomes Processed. If every item is denied, it becomes Denied. After accepted items are finalised, the request can display Refunded while individual items remain Denied.</p>\n<h3>Partially fulfilled quantities</h3><p>Use a return for dispatched units and a cancellation for undispatched units, then confirm that the combined customer refund and remittance adjustments reconcile.</p>","Connected and API Workflows":"<p>A connected system can create and progress Refund Requests through GraphQL.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>State</th><th>Workflow meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>PENDING_APPROVAL</code></td><td>Seller must accept, deny or require a return.</td></tr><tr><td><code>AWAITING_RETURN</code></td><td>A physical return is already required.</td></tr><tr><td><code>REFUND_ACCEPTED</code></td><td>No further Seller approval is required.</td></tr><tr><td><code>DENIED</code></td><td>The Line Item is rejected.</td></tr><tr><td><code>REFUNDED</code></td><td>Operator finalisation is complete.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>The integration should preserve external references, use the correct Invoice and Line Item IDs, prevent duplicates, synchronise evidence and outcomes, coordinate customer communication and payment, and reconcile the Invoice Amendment.</p>","Monitoring and Exceptions":"<p>Monitor aged Awaiting requests, Sellers who have not completed Action Refund, returned items awaiting assessment, missing tracking, wrong return addresses, returnless refunds awaiting finalisation, disputed denials, duplicates, failed payment refunds and remittance mismatches.</p>\n<h3>Seller has not acted</h3><p>Confirm notification delivery, user access, request visibility, Seller understanding and the response SLA.</p>\n<h3>Customer has not returned the item</h3><p>Confirm the instructions, deadline, tracking and whether the request should remain open, be denied or be escalated.</p>\n<h3>Tracking shows delivery but Seller has not acted</h3><p>Send the Seller the Refund Request ID, Invoice ID, tracking, delivery date, affected items and response deadline.</p>\n<h3>Payment refund fails after approval</h3><p>Do not create another Refund Request. Resolve the payment through the approved process and retain the successful refund reference.</p>","Test the Return Workflow":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Operator and authorised Seller can initiate a post-dispatch request</li><li>Request begins as Awaiting</li><li>Seller can deny, approve Do Not Return or require Return</li><li>Carrier, tracking, notes and attachments are recorded</li><li>Customer receives return instructions</li><li>Seller can accept or deny the returned item</li><li>Accepted items become Processed</li><li>Operator finalises and the payment refund succeeds</li><li>Invoice Amendment, fees and remittance are correct</li><li>Mixed accepted, returned and denied outcomes work</li><li>Dispatched and undispatched quantities use separate workflows</li><li>Duplicate requests are prevented</li></ul>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Post-dispatch and denial reasons are configured</li><li>Return eligibility is documented</li><li>Seller initiation permissions are configured</li><li>Sellers understand Action Refund and Action Return</li><li>Returnless and return-required criteria are documented</li><li>Return-postage and prepaid-label ownership are agreed</li><li>Customer communication has an owner</li><li>Return deadlines and assessment SLAs are defined</li><li>Operator escalation and override rules are documented</li><li>Mixed and partially fulfilled outcomes are tested</li><li>Processed requests are monitored</li><li>Payment and remittance reconciliation is understood</li></ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/13277938134029-Initiate-a-refund-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Initiate a refund as a Seller</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/13278067225741-Action-a-refund-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Action a refund as a Seller</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/13278182781837-Action-a-return-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Action a return as a Seller</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24105463369101-Approve-a-return\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Approve a return</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24104906898061-Decline-a-return\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Decline a return</a></li><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/refunds/howto_advancedrefund/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to use the refunds flow</a></li></ul>"},"related":[["refund-foundations","Refund Foundations"],["refund-configuration","Refund Configuration"],["cancellation-workflow","Cancellation Workflow"],["refund-statuses","Refund Statuses"],["refund-financial-adjustments","Refund Financial Adjustments"]]},"refund-statuses":{"summary":"Read Refund Request and Line Item statuses correctly, identify who must act next, and monitor cancellations and returns through to completion.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Seller management","Finance","Technology"],"sections":{"Understand the Two Status Levels":"<p>Every refund has two related status levels:</p><ol><li><strong>Refund Request status</strong>, which summarises the overall request.</li><li><strong>Refund Request Line Item status</strong>, which records each affected item or adjustment.</li></ol>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><div class=\"structure-node\"><strong>Refund Request: Awaiting</strong></div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↓</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Line Item A: Pending Approval<br>Line Item B: Awaiting Return<br>Line Item C: Denied</div></div>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Use the Refund Request status to find the queue. Use the Line Item statuses and Actions column to understand the work.</strong></div>","Refund Request Statuses":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Status</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Who acts next</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Awaiting</strong></td><td>A post-dispatch decision or return step is unfinished.</td><td>Seller or Operator</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Processed</strong></td><td>Accepted items are ready for Operator financial finalisation.</td><td>Operator</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Refunded</strong></td><td>The Operator has finalised the accepted refund in Marketplacer.</td><td>Workflow complete in Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Denied</strong></td><td>Every Refund Request Line Item is denied.</td><td>No action unless denial is reverted</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3>Awaiting</h3><p>The request may be waiting for a Seller decision, physical return, returned-item assessment or an eligible Operator action.</p>\n<h3>Processed</h3><p>The request is ready for <strong>Process Refund</strong>. This includes pre-dispatch cancellations, returnless approvals and accepted physical returns.</p>\n<h3>Refunded</h3><p>The Invoice Amendment is created and Marketplacer finalisation is complete. Confirm the customer payment separately.</p>\n<h3>Denied</h3><p>Every request Line Item has been rejected. Mixed requests with refunded and denied items can display as Refunded overall.</p>","Refund Request Line Item Statuses":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Line Item status</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Typical next step</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Pending Approval</strong></td><td>The Seller must decide how the refund proceeds.</td><td>Accept, require return or deny</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Awaiting Return</strong></td><td>A physical return is required and not yet accepted or denied.</td><td>Receive and assess item</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Refund Accepted</strong></td><td>Required Seller and return actions are complete.</td><td>Operator finalises</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Refunded</strong></td><td>The Operator has finalised this item.</td><td>Complete</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Denied</strong></td><td>The item will not be refunded.</td><td>Complete unless denial is reverted</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><strong>Action Refund</strong> normally corresponds to Pending Approval. <strong>Action Return</strong> normally corresponds to Awaiting Return.</p>","How Line Item Statuses Control the Request":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Line Item combination</th><th>Request status</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>One or more Pending Approval</td><td>Awaiting</td></tr><tr><td>One or more Awaiting Return</td><td>Awaiting</td></tr><tr><td>Refund Accepted with no unresolved items</td><td>Processed</td></tr><tr><td>Refund Accepted plus Denied</td><td>Processed</td></tr><tr><td>All accepted items Refunded</td><td>Refunded</td></tr><tr><td>Refunded plus Denied</td><td>Refunded</td></tr><tr><td>All items Denied</td><td>Denied</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>The unresolved Line Item takes priority. A request containing Refund Accepted, Pending Approval and Denied remains Awaiting until the pending item is actioned.</p>","Read the Status and Action Together":"<h3>Operator Portal</h3><p>Go to <strong>Orders → Refund Requests</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Status</th><th>Typical action</th><th>Check</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Awaiting</td><td>View, Process Return or wait for Seller</td><td>Line Item status and current owner</td></tr><tr><td>Processed</td><td>Process Refund</td><td>Financial adjustments and payment refund</td></tr><tr><td>Refunded</td><td>View</td><td>Payment confirmation and reconciliation</td></tr><tr><td>Denied</td><td>View or Revert Denial</td><td>Reason, evidence and policy</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3>Seller Portal</h3><p>Go to <strong>Orders → All Refund Requests</strong>. Action Refund requires the Seller decision. Action Return requires returned-item assessment. No Seller action appears after Refund Accepted, Refunded or Denied.</p>","Status Progression by Workflow":"<h3>Pre-dispatch cancellation</h3><p><strong>Processed → Refunded</strong></p>\n<h3>Post-dispatch returnless refund</h3><p><strong>Awaiting / Pending Approval → Processed / Refund Accepted → Refunded</strong></p>\n<h3>Post-dispatch return required</h3><p><strong>Awaiting / Pending Approval → Awaiting / Awaiting Return → Processed / Refund Accepted → Refunded</strong></p>\n<h3>Fully denied request</h3><p><strong>Awaiting → Denied</strong></p>\n<h3>Mixed request</h3><p>Refunded items and Denied items can produce an overall <strong>Refunded</strong> request. Review each Line Item before communicating the outcome.</p>","Mixed Line Item Outcomes":"<p>Mixed requests require Line Item review during customer communication, payment reconciliation, Seller remittance review, disputes and reporting.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Line Item</th><th>Final outcome</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Jacket</td><td>Refunded</td></tr><tr><td>Shoes</td><td>Denied</td></tr><tr><td>Delivery fee</td><td>Not refunded</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Provide the customer with an itemised explanation of what was refunded, what was denied, why, whether postage was included and the total cash returned.</p>","Denied Refunds and Reverting Denial":"<p>Use <strong>Revert Denial</strong> after reviewing additional evidence, resolving a policy dispute, identifying a Seller error or approving an exception.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Orders → Refund Requests</strong>, filter by <strong>Denied</strong>, open the request, review every Line Item and select <strong>Revert Denial</strong>.</p>\n<p>The request moves to <strong>Processed</strong> and bypasses another Seller approval step. The Operator must still process the refund and confirm the customer payment.</p>\n<p>Record why the denial was overturned, who approved it, which items are affected, the final customer amount and the Seller remittance effect.</p>","Operator Permissions":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Permission</th><th>Access provided</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>View refund requests</strong></td><td>View and export requests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Process returns</strong></td><td>Start requests and process returns.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Process refunds</strong></td><td>Finalise refunds.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Revert refund denial</strong></td><td>Reopen denied requests.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>These permissions build on one another. Use role separation where Finance or operational controls require different users to create, approve, finalise and reverse decisions.</p>","Monitor Refund Queues":"<h3>Awaiting</h3><p>Monitor requests awaiting Seller decisions, missing tracking, overdue customer returns, delivered parcels awaiting assessment and aged greyed-out actions.</p>\n<h3>Processed</h3><p>Monitor cancellations, returnless approvals and accepted returns awaiting financial finalisation. Leaving Processed requests unresolved delays the customer refund.</p>\n<h3>Refunded</h3><p>Reconcile payment references, Invoice Amendments, credit notes, remittance and connected-system status.</p>\n<h3>Denied</h3><p>Review repeated Seller denials, missing evidence, customer disputes, inconsistent policy and denial reversals.</p>","Troubleshoot Unexpected Statuses":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Issue</th><th>Review</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cancellation is Awaiting</td><td>Confirm the starting workflow or API Line Item state.</td></tr><tr><td>Returnless refund remains Awaiting</td><td>Check whether every item was approved and no item remains pending.</td></tr><tr><td>Returned item remains Awaiting</td><td>Check whether Action Return was completed.</td></tr><tr><td>Processed but no action visible</td><td>Confirm Operator permissions.</td></tr><tr><td>Refunded but customer has no funds</td><td>Check the payment gateway or connected workflow.</td></tr><tr><td>Refunded although one item was denied</td><td>This is expected when another item was refunded.</td></tr><tr><td>Seller cannot find the request</td><td>Check ownership, permissions, filters and notification delivery.</td></tr><tr><td>Storefront differs from Marketplacer</td><td>Review integration logs, webhook handling and external references.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","Test Refund Statuses":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Cancellation begins as Processed</li><li>Operator finalisation changes Processed to Refunded</li><li>Post-dispatch request begins as Awaiting</li><li>Pending Approval shows Action Refund</li><li>Return Required keeps the request Awaiting</li><li>Accepting the returned item changes the request to Processed</li><li>Denying every item changes the request to Denied</li><li>Mixed accepted and denied items behave correctly</li><li>Revert Denial moves the request to Processed</li><li>User permissions restrict finalisation and reversal</li><li>Payment failure is detected even when Marketplacer shows Refunded</li></ul>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Teams understand request and Line Item statuses</li><li>Status and Action are read together</li><li>Awaiting and Processed queues have owners</li><li>Seller response and assessment SLAs are defined</li><li>Finance understands Processed is not a completed payment refund</li><li>Payment reconciliation continues after Refunded</li><li>Mixed outcomes are reviewed individually</li><li>Denials include reasons and evidence</li><li>Denial reversal approval is documented</li><li>Operator roles support separation of duties</li><li>Status transitions are tested in Sandbox</li><li>Aged requests are reported and escalated</li></ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/refunds/howto_advancedrefund/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to use the refunds flow</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/8837682695053-Search-and-find-orders-in-the-Seller-Portal\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Search and find orders in the Seller Portal</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24105251849229-Returns-FAQs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Returns FAQs</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/28925785268365-Operator-user-role-permissions\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Operator user role permissions</a></li></ul>"},"related":[["refund-foundations","Refund Foundations"],["cancellation-workflow","Cancellation Workflow"],["return-workflow","Return Workflow"],["refund-financial-adjustments","Refund Financial Adjustments"],["order-exceptions","Order Exceptions"]]},"refund-financial-adjustments":{"summary":"Finalise the financial outcome of a cancellation or return by confirming the customer refund, deciding which fees are reversed or retained, creating the Invoice Amendment and reconciling Seller remittance.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Finance","Customer service","Seller management","Technology"],"sections":{"Understand Financial Finalisation":"<p>Once a Refund Request reaches <strong>Processed</strong>, the Operator confirms the financial outcome.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Orders → Refund Requests → Processed → Process Refund</strong>.</p>\n<ol><li>Review accepted Line Items and quantities.</li><li>Review the customer cash refund.</li><li>Review the Seller remittance adjustment.</li><li>Adjust commission, merchant fees, postage and other amounts where required.</li><li>Select <strong>Mark as Refunded</strong>.</li><li>Complete or verify the actual payment refund.</li></ol>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Do not treat financial finalisation as a status-only task.</strong> Confirm both the amount returned to the customer and the amount recovered from or returned to the Seller.</div>","Review the Original Transaction":"<p>Review the original Seller Invoice before changing any values.</p>\n<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Original Line Items and quantities</li><li>Item prices, discounts and tax</li><li>Postage and postage tax</li><li>Commission and commission tax</li><li>Merchant fees and tax</li><li>Promotion funding</li><li>Original Seller remittance</li><li>Whether the Seller has already been paid</li><li>Previous Invoice Amendments for the same quantity</li></ul>\n<p>The original Invoice remains the record of what was purchased. The Invoice Amendment records what changed later.</p>","Separate Customer and Seller Outcomes":"<p>A refund has two connected financial outcomes.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Outcome</th><th>Question</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Customer refund</strong></td><td>How much money should be returned to the shopper?</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Seller remittance adjustment</strong></td><td>How much should be recovered from, retained from or returned to the Seller?</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>The amounts are not always identical. The Operator may fund goodwill, retain a merchant fee, reverse commission, refund only part of the original postage or apply a Seller-only correction.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Review both perspectives.</strong> Changing the customer refund does not automatically guarantee the intended Seller outcome.</div>","Process the Refund":"<p>The Process Refund page can include refunded items, additional adjustments, commission refund, merchant-fee refund, remittance-only controls, notes, evidence, total refund and Remittance to Reclaim.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Check</th><th>Question</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Line Items</td><td>Are the correct products and quantities included?</td></tr><tr><td>Customer amount</td><td>Does the total match the approved outcome?</td></tr><tr><td>Postage</td><td>Is original delivery refunded, retained or partially refunded?</td></tr><tr><td>Commission</td><td>Is the Operator retaining or reversing commission?</td></tr><tr><td>Merchant fee</td><td>Is the fee returned to the Seller or retained?</td></tr><tr><td>Tax</td><td>Are the applicable tax components correct?</td></tr><tr><td>Remittance</td><td>Is the correct amount being recovered from the Seller?</td></tr><tr><td>Payment</td><td>Who executes the actual customer refund?</td></tr></tbody></table></div>","Adjust Refunded Line Items":"<p>Confirm quantity, original price, discounts, item tax and whether the customer receives a full or partial item refund.</p>\n<h3>Full Line Item refund</h3><p>Refund the complete accepted value for the approved quantity.</p>\n<h3>Partial quantity refund</h3><p>Select only the affected quantity, for example one unit from a quantity of three.</p>\n<h3>Partial-value refund</h3><p>Use an approved negative adjustment to reduce the starting refund where policy permits, and document the reason, approval, customer agreement, Seller funding and tax treatment.</p>","Refund Postage":"<p>Original delivery charges may be refunded in full, refunded partially, retained or allocated across refunded and unaffected Line Items.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Possible treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Entire Invoice cancelled before dispatch</td><td>Refund all customer postage</td></tr><tr><td>One item cancelled while others ship</td><td>Retain or recalculate under policy</td></tr><tr><td>Seller sends wrong item</td><td>Refund applicable original delivery and return costs</td></tr><tr><td>Change of mind</td><td>Original postage may be retained under policy</td></tr><tr><td>Returnless partial refund</td><td>Postage may remain unchanged</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Use <strong>Add Line Item</strong> to add an approved postage refund that is not already included. A positive amount increases the customer refund.</p>","Refund Commission to the Seller":"<p><strong>Refund commission to Seller</strong> determines whether the Operator reverses some or all of the commission originally charged.</p>\n<p>Reverse commission where the refunded sale should no longer attract commission. Retain it only where the approved Seller agreement and marketplace policy permit this.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Review partial refunds carefully.</strong> The field may initially reflect commission for the complete Invoice. Do not reverse commission for unaffected Line Items.</div>","Refund the Merchant Fee":"<p><strong>Refund merchant fee</strong> determines whether the Operator returns some or all of the merchant fee to the Seller.</p>\n<p>Return the fee where the commercial model requires the Operator to absorb it. Retain it where the payment provider does not return the fee or the Seller agreement keeps it payable after refund.</p>\n<p>The Marketplacer merchant fee and the external payment-provider fee may differ. Finance should confirm the actual provider outcome.</p>","Manage Commission on Postage":"<p>Commission can also apply to Line Item postage.</p>\n<p>Review <strong>Configuration → Finance Settings → Commission Settings → Exclude line item postage commission from refunds</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Outcome</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Exclusion disabled</td><td>Applicable postage commission can be reversed during refund processing.</td></tr><tr><td>Exclusion enabled</td><td>The Operator retains postage commission on refunded transactions.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>The Seller agreement should explain whether commission on original shipping remains payable after cancellation or return.</p>","Use Only Adjust Remittance":"<p><strong>Only adjust remittance</strong> is a per-adjustment control on the final <strong>Process Refund</strong> page. It is not a global Finance or Remittance setting.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Orders → Refund Requests</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Filter by Processed</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Select Process Refund</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Apply the control to the relevant adjustment</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Verify Total Refund Cash and Remittance to Reclaim</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>Select Mark as Refunded</strong></div></div></div>\n<h3>When the checkbox is not selected</h3><p>Leave it unselected when the adjustment should affect both the customer refund and the Seller remittance outcome.</p>\n<div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Refund original postage</h3><p>Add a $10 postage refund to a $100 item refund. The customer receives $110 and the corresponding Seller-funded amount participates in remittance.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Partial-refund deduction</h3><p>Reduce a $19.99 starting refund by $4.99. The customer receives $15 and the related Seller recovery is reduced.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Seller-funded goodwill</h3><p>Add $10 customer goodwill where the Seller has agreed to fund it. The customer and Seller outcomes both change.</p></article></div>\n<h3>When the checkbox is selected</h3><p>Select it when the adjustment should change the Seller's financial position without changing what the customer receives.</p>\n<div class=\"card-grid\"><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Return commission to the Seller</h3><p>The customer receives the approved $100 refund. A $10 commission reversal reduces Seller recovery without giving the customer another $10.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Return the merchant fee</h3><p>The customer amount remains unchanged while a $2 merchant-fee adjustment changes the Seller remittance position.</p></article><article class=\"info-card\"><h3>Seller-only correction</h3><p>Finance corrects the Seller balance after the customer has already received the right amount.</p></article></div>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>Decision</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Should this amount change what the customer receives?</td><td>Leave Only adjust remittance unselected.</td></tr><tr><td>Should it change only the Seller position?</td><td>Select Only adjust remittance.</td></tr><tr><td>Is the funding outcome unclear?</td><td>Do not finalise until Finance confirms it.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Review both totals after every change.</strong> Positive and negative amounts can move the Seller balance in the opposite direction from the intended outcome.</div>","Apply Partial Refunds and Other Adjustments":"<p>Use <strong>Add Line Item</strong> for an approved financial adjustment that is not represented by the original refunded product Line Items.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Positive adjustment</th><th>Negative adjustment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Refund postage, reimburse return postage, add goodwill, refund a service charge</td><td>Agreed partial-value deduction, retained postage, permitted return-cost deduction</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Where the field is <strong>Amount per item</strong>, confirm whether it is multiplied by quantity. Review the final displayed total rather than relying on the input value alone.</p>","Understand Invoice Amendments":"<p>Selecting <strong>Mark as Refunded</strong> creates an Invoice Amendment linked to the original Seller Invoice.</p>\n<p>The amendment can record refunded item value and quantity, tax, postage, commission, merchant fees, other financial adjustments and remittance recovery.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><div class=\"structure-node\"><strong>Original Seller Invoice</strong></div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">├</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Invoice Amendment 1<br>Cancellation of Line Item A</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">└</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Invoice Amendment 2<br>Later return of Line Item B</div></div>\n<p>The original Invoice is not overwritten. Operators can review amendments against the original Invoice and in financial reporting.</p>","Remittance Effects":"<p>Finalising a refund creates an Invoice Amendment and recalculates the amount owed to the Seller. The Process Refund page displays <strong>Remittance to Reclaim</strong>.</p>\n<p>The customer refund and Seller recovery are connected, but they may differ because of commission, merchant fees, postage, Operator-funded amounts and remittance-only entries.</p>\n<h3>Before the Seller is paid</h3><p>The Invoice Amendment reduces the Seller payable balance before the next payout.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Financial record</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Original Seller remittance</td><td>$150</td></tr><tr><td>Remittance to Reclaim</td><td>-$60</td></tr><tr><td>Revised amount payable</td><td>$90</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3>After the Seller is paid</h3><p>The Invoice Amendment creates a recovery that reduces later eligible Seller earnings. The Operator does not normally reverse the exact original bank payment.</p>\n<h3>Worked example: refund after remittance was paid</h3>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Setting</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Remittance delay</td><td>14 days</td></tr><tr><td>Remittance schedule</td><td>Daily</td></tr><tr><td>Original Seller remittance</td><td>$200</td></tr><tr><td>Times</td><td>Marketplace local time</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Date</th><th>Event</th><th>Seller position</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1 July, 10:00 am</td><td>Seller dispatches the complete Invoice</td><td>+$200</td></tr><tr><td>15 July, 10:00 am</td><td>The 14-day remittance delay has passed</td><td>+$200 eligible</td></tr><tr><td>16 July, nightly run</td><td>The Invoice passes completion, payment release, delay and schedule checks</td><td>+$200</td></tr><tr><td>16 July</td><td>Remittance Advice is generated and the payout process pays the Seller</td><td>$0 outstanding</td></tr><tr><td>20 July</td><td>Customer requests a post-dispatch return</td><td>$0</td></tr><tr><td>22 July</td><td>Seller accepts the returned item</td><td>$0</td></tr><tr><td>23 July</td><td>Operator marks the request as Refunded</td><td>-$200 recovery</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Because the parent Invoice has already been remitted, the completed Invoice Amendment can participate in a later remittance cycle.</p>\n<h3>Nightly run with a negative balance</h3>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Eligible record</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Other eligible Seller Sales</td><td>+$120</td></tr><tr><td>Refund recovery</td><td>-$200</td></tr><tr><td>Eligible Seller total</td><td><strong>-$80</strong></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>No Remittance Advice is generated while the eligible total is zero or negative. The records remain in the Seller's unprocessed remittance position.</p>\n<h3>A later Sale makes the balance positive</h3>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Eligible record</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Carried recovery</td><td>-$80</td></tr><tr><td>Newly eligible Seller Invoice</td><td>+$150</td></tr><tr><td>New positive total</td><td><strong>+$70</strong></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>A Remittance Advice can now be generated for $70. The earlier refund recovery is offset before the Seller receives the remaining value.</p>\n<h3>Remittance schedule</h3><p>The nightly process evaluates eligibility. A daily Seller can be processed on the next eligible nightly run. A weekly or monthly Seller is included only when the configured schedule is due.</p>\n<h3>Why Operators use a remittance delay</h3><p>A delay such as <strong>14 days</strong> gives time for delivery, early customer issues, Seller assessment and Operator finalisation before the payout. This reduces the likelihood of post-payment recovery.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>A 14-day delay reduces post-payment refund recovery, but it does not prevent it.</strong> Returns can occur after the delay, so the Operator must be prepared to carry negative Seller balances forward.</div>\n<p>Choose the delay based on delivery time, return window, Seller risk, product value, trading volume, payout frequency and commercial terms. Some marketplaces apply longer Seller-specific delays for higher-risk Sellers or categories.</p>\n<h3>Review the remittance outcome</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Invoice Amendment exists</li><li>Remittance to Reclaim is correct</li><li>Customer-funded and Operator-funded amounts are separated</li><li>Commission and merchant-fee treatment follows policy</li><li>The amendment appears in the expected remittance cycle</li><li>Remittance Advice and actual payout agree</li><li>Duplicate external recovery is prevented</li></ul>","Generate and Review Credit Notes":"<p>Where credit notes are enabled, Invoice Amendments generate financial documents.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Credit note</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Seller credit note</strong></td><td>Records the refund against the customer-facing Seller Invoice.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Commission credit note</strong></td><td>Records the Operator commission adjustment.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Enable under <strong>Configuration → Finance Settings → Enable credit notes</strong>. Download from <strong>Orders → All Sales</strong> using the Credit Note PDFs column.</p>\n<p>Finance should confirm that credit-note behaviour matches the marketplace's tax and invoicing model.</p>","Reconcile the Complete Refund":"<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><div class=\"structure-node\">Customer payment refund</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Payment gateway transaction</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Storefront Order</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Marketplacer Refund Request</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Invoice Amendment and credit notes</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Seller remittance</div></div>\n<p>Confirm the customer amount and reference, Marketplacer request and amendment, commission and fee adjustments, Remittance to Reclaim, credit notes and external accounting record.</p>\n<p>The Refunds report can support reconciliation by showing requested amount, cash amount refunded, remitted status, payment gateway, transaction ID and refund log.</p>","Worked Financial Example":"<p>A customer purchases an item for $100 plus $10 postage. The Operator originally charges $10 commission and a $2 merchant fee.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Item</td><td>$100</td></tr><tr><td>Postage</td><td>$10</td></tr><tr><td>Customer total</td><td>$110</td></tr><tr><td>Commission</td><td>$10</td></tr><tr><td>Merchant fee</td><td>$2</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>The item is faulty. The policy refunds item and postage, reverses commission and returns the merchant fee to the Seller.</p>\n<p>The payment gateway returns $110 to the customer. The Invoice Amendment and remittance calculation must also reverse the approved Seller and Operator amounts.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Use the approved commercial decision, not a default assumption.</strong> Another marketplace may retain the merchant fee or postage commission.</div>","Monitor Financial Exceptions":"<p>Monitor Processed requests not finalised, Marketplacer Refunded with no successful payment, payment completed with no Invoice Amendment, mismatched totals, full-Invoice commission applied to a partial refund, duplicated postage, incorrect positive or negative signs, incorrect remittance-only selection, duplicate external recovery, missing credit notes and long-standing negative Seller balances.</p>\n<h3>Customer amount correct, Seller recovery wrong</h3><p>Review Only adjust remittance, commission, merchant fee, added Line Items, signs and the original remittance state.</p>\n<h3>Seller recovery correct, customer amount wrong</h3><p>Review the payment transaction, added adjustments, postage, deductions, rounding and duplicate external payment.</p>\n<h3>Amendment missing from remittance</h3><p>Confirm that the request was finalised, the amendment exists, the parent Invoice remittance state, the next remittance cycle and Seller remittance details.</p>","Test Refund Financial Adjustments":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Full and partial item refunds</li><li>Partial quantity refund</li><li>Postage refunded, retained and added manually</li><li>Commission fully reversed, partially reversed and retained</li><li>Merchant fee reversed and retained</li><li>Postage commission excluded where configured</li><li>Positive and negative adjustments</li><li>Only adjust remittance selected and unselected examples</li><li>Operator-funded goodwill</li><li>Refund before Seller payment</li><li>Recovery after Seller payment</li><li>Negative balance carried forward</li><li>Invoice Amendment and credit notes generated</li><li>Payment gateway and remittance totals reconcile</li><li>Duplicate refund and recovery are prevented</li></ul>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Finance understands the Process Refund page</li><li>Customer refund and Seller recovery are reviewed separately</li><li>Postage, commission, merchant-fee and postage-commission policies are approved</li><li>Teams know where and when Only adjust remittance is used</li><li>Positive and negative adjustment rules are documented</li><li>Partial refunds require notes and approval</li><li>Remittance recovery after Seller payment is understood</li><li>Remittance delays and schedules are configured intentionally</li><li>Negative Seller balances have an operating process</li><li>Duplicate external deductions are prevented</li><li>Credit notes are enabled or deliberately disabled</li><li>Payment references are retained</li><li>Refund Request, Invoice Amendment and remittance totals reconcile</li></ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24105463369101-Approve-a-return\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Approve a return</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360050107431-Refund-recovery\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Refund recovery</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360052908272-Seller-payments-and-remittance-workflow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Seller payments and remittance workflow</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/16214109276045-Understanding-remittance-advices\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Understanding remittance advices</a></li><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/sellers/howto_remittance_advice/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Remittance Advice API workflow</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/28925550144269-Credit-notes-overview\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Credit notes overview</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/38122804710029-Managing-Commission-on-Postage-and-Refunds\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Managing Commission on Postage and Refunds</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/31442688192269-Refunds-report\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Refunds report</a></li></ul>"},"related":[["refund-foundations","Refund Foundations"],["refund-statuses","Refund Statuses"],["cancellation-workflow","Cancellation Workflow"],["return-workflow","Return Workflow"],["remittances","Remittances"]]},"refund-disputes":{"summary":"Resolve denied, disputed and unusual Refund Requests consistently by reviewing evidence, applying marketplace policy, recording the decision and aligning customer, Seller, payment and remittance outcomes.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Seller management","Finance","Technology"],"sections":{"Use a Controlled Resolution Process":"<p>Use the dispute and exception process when a Seller denies a request, rejects a returned item, the Operator disagrees, evidence conflicts, a parcel is damaged or missing, the standard return path cannot be completed, or Marketplacer and payment records do not agree.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Identify the Invoice and affected items</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Confirm fulfilment and refund status</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Gather evidence</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Apply policy and authority</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Approve, deny or overturn</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>Reconcile and communicate</strong></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Do not create a second Refund Request to avoid resolving the first one.</strong> Review the existing request, Line Items and status before taking another action.</div>","Establish Decision Authority":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Recommended owner</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer eligibility</td><td>Customer Service or Marketplace Operations</td></tr><tr><td>Whether a physical return is required</td><td>Seller or Operator under policy</td></tr><tr><td>Returned-item condition</td><td>Seller, supported by evidence</td></tr><tr><td>Whether a Seller denial is upheld</td><td>Marketplace Operations</td></tr><tr><td>Policy exception</td><td>Named Operator approver</td></tr><tr><td>Who funds goodwill</td><td>Finance or authorised Operations lead</td></tr><tr><td>Commission and fee treatment</td><td>Finance under the Seller agreement</td></tr><tr><td>Customer communication</td><td>Customer Service</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Define approval thresholds for high-value refunds, regulated products, repeated claims, repeated Seller denials, refunds after Seller payment and exceptions outside policy.</p>","Gather the Evidence":"<p>Review customer request, Seller Invoice, product listing, dispatch and delivery records, customer and Seller images, serial or batch details, return tracking, notes, payment records and previous Invoice Amendments.</p>\n<p>Every denied or overturned request should record the affected Line Items and quantities, the reason, evidence, policy, decision maker, date, customer outcome, Seller outcome and approved exception.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Use meaningful notes.</strong> Avoid entries such as Not approved or Seller declined without explaining why.</div>","Seller Denial":"<h3>Seller denies the original request</h3><p>In <strong>Orders → All Refund Requests → Action Refund</strong>, the Seller selects the items, chooses a Deny Refund Reason, adds notes and evidence, then selects <strong>Deny Refund</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Seller denies the returned item</h3><p>In <strong>Action Return</strong>, the Seller records the returned-item assessment, chooses the denial reason, adds evidence and selects <strong>Deny Return</strong>.</p>\n<p>If every Line Item is denied, the request becomes Denied. If some items are accepted, the request continues according to those items.</p>\n<div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>A Seller denial is not automatically the final marketplace decision.</strong> Review policy and evidence before communicating the result.</div>","Operator Denial":"<p>An Operator can deny an eligible Line Item on the return-required path.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Orders → Refund Requests → Awaiting → Process Return → Deny Refund</strong>.</p>\n<p>Use Operator denial when the return does not meet policy, the customer did not complete the required return, the returned item does not match or an Operator-owned investigation reaches a denied outcome.</p>\n<p>The Operator must communicate the result to the customer.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>Inventory is not restored automatically by the return decision.</strong> The Seller or connected source system must reconcile the physical stock and update availability.</div>","Revert a Denial":"<p>Use <strong>Revert Denial</strong> when the Operator decides that a denied request should proceed because of new evidence, Seller error, delivery confirmation, an approved exception or an incorrect original decision.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Orders → Refund Requests → Denied → View → Revert Denial</strong>.</p>\n<p>The request moves to <strong>Processed</strong>. The Operator must then select <strong>Process Refund</strong>, review the financial adjustments, select <strong>Mark as Refunded</strong> and complete the customer payment.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Revert Denial does not send money to the customer.</strong> It reopens the Marketplacer financial workflow.</div>\n<p>The Operator user requires <strong>Revert refund denial</strong> and its dependent refund permissions.</p>","Damaged Item":"<p>Confirm when the damage occurred, whether the item is safe to return, packaging condition, Carrier involvement, product value, evidence and who funds item, shipping and fee costs.</p>\n<h3>Returnless path</h3><p>Use Do Not Return where the item is unsafe, destroyed, low value or sufficiently evidenced.</p>\n<h3>Return-required path</h3><p>Require return for inspection, warranty investigation, manufacturer review or where evidence is inconclusive.</p>\n<p>Retain images of the item and packaging, shipping label, tracking, serial or batch number, delivery date and Seller assessment.</p>","Incorrect Item":"<p>Compare the original Invoice Line Item and Variant with the delivered product, SKU, barcode, packaging, warehouse record and customer images.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Outcome</th><th>Workflow</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer keeps the item and receives refund</td><td>Returnless refund</td></tr><tr><td>Incorrect item must be returned</td><td>Return required</td></tr><tr><td>Correct item sent separately</td><td>Approved replacement or new-order process</td></tr><tr><td>Customer accepts a partial refund</td><td>Approved partial financial adjustment</td></tr><tr><td>Evidence does not support the claim</td><td>Deny with reason and evidence</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Keep the refund against the original Seller Invoice and separately record any replacement process.</p>","Lost Parcel":"<p>A dispatched but undelivered parcel follows the post-dispatch workflow. Where loss is confirmed and the customer has no item to return, use the <strong>Do Not Return</strong> path.</p>\n<p>Review Carrier tracking, latest event, delivery address, delivery photo or signature, dispatch date, Carrier investigation, customer history and whether a replacement or refund already exists.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Keep the customer refund separate from the Carrier claim.</strong> Prevent duplicate reimbursement when a replacement or compensation has already been provided.</div>","Change of Mind":"<p>Confirm product eligibility, return period, opened or used condition, packaging, tags and accessories, return-postage ownership, original postage treatment and permitted deductions.</p>\n<p>A change-of-mind return normally requires the item to be returned and assessed. The Seller verifies the correct item, resalable condition, packaging, signs of wear, timing and category-specific rules.</p>\n<p>Apply one marketplace standard unless Seller-specific terms have been deliberately approved and clearly communicated.</p>","Partial Refund":"<p>Use a partial refund when the approved customer outcome is less than the full value of the affected Line Item or quantity.</p>\n<h3>Partial quantity</h3><p>Select only the affected quantity.</p>\n<h3>Partial value</h3><p>During <strong>Orders → Refund Requests → Processed → Process Refund</strong>, add the approved negative adjustment before selecting Mark as Refunded.</p>\n<p>Document the original value, agreed customer amount, approval, customer agreement, Seller-funded and Operator-funded portions, postage, commission, fees and final Remittance to Reclaim.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>A partial refund is a financial outcome, not a shortcut around an unresolved dispute.</strong></div>","Mixed Line Item Outcomes":"<p>One request can contain accepted, return-required and denied items. It remains Awaiting while any item is pending or awaiting return.</p>\n<p>After accepted items are finalised, the overall request may display Refunded while individual items remain Denied. Base customer communication and payment calculation on each Line Item, not the overall request status.</p>","Financial and Remittance Effects":"<h3>Denial upheld</h3><p>No accepted refund is finalised and no refund Invoice Amendment should be created for the denied amount. Investigate any external customer payment that has already occurred.</p>\n<h3>Denial reverted</h3><p>Revert Denial moves the request to Processed. The Operator then reviews the customer cash refund, item and postage values, commission, merchant fees, funding split, Remittance to Reclaim and whether the Seller has already been paid.</p>\n<h3>Customer already refunded externally</h3><ol><li>Confirm the payment amount and reference.</li><li>Do not issue another payment.</li><li>Resolve the existing Marketplacer request.</li><li>Finalise the Invoice Amendment and Seller remittance effect.</li><li>Reconcile every system.</li></ol>","Customer and Seller Communication":"<p>The final communication should identify affected items and quantities, accepted and denied outcomes, reasons, return requirements, evidence reviewed, refund amount, postage treatment, expected payment timing and escalation route.</p>\n<p>When a denial is overturned, tell the Seller why, which items are affected, the refund amount, the remittance effect, commission and fee treatment and whether further action is required.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\"><strong>A denial reversal should not arrive as an unexplained remittance deduction.</strong></div>","Escalation and Monitoring":"<h3>Operational review</h3><p>Customer Service or Operations reviews the request, notes, evidence, delivery state and policy.</p>\n<h3>Policy decision</h3><p>Escalate conflicting evidence, unclear policy, high-value cases, Seller-specific exceptions and repeated dispute patterns.</p>\n<h3>Finance or integration review</h3><p>Escalate when the customer has already been paid, the amount is wrong, the amendment is missing, remittance does not reconcile or systems disagree.</p>\n<h3>Marketplacer Support</h3><p>Raise Support when platform behaviour cannot be explained through status, permissions, reasons, workflow history, integration logs and payment records. Include environment, Refund Request ID, Invoice ID, affected items, expected and actual results, screenshots and timestamps.</p>\n<p>Monitor aged disputes, repeated denial reversals, Seller denial rates, missing evidence, return deliveries awaiting assessment, external payments, partial refunds and negative Seller balances.</p>","Test Dispute Scenarios":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Seller denies the original request</li><li>Seller denies a returned item</li><li>Mixed accepted and denied items behave correctly</li><li>Operator denies an eligible Awaiting Return item</li><li>Permissions restrict denial and reversal</li><li>Revert Denial moves the request to Processed</li><li>Customer payment is issued once only</li><li>Damaged item follows returnless and return-required paths</li><li>Incorrect item and replacement process are controlled</li><li>Lost parcel uses Do Not Return where approved</li><li>Change-of-mind acceptance and denial are tested</li><li>Partial quantity and partial value calculate correctly</li><li>Remittance to Reclaim reconciles</li><li>Inventory is updated by the Seller or source system</li></ul>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Decision authority and approval thresholds are documented</li><li>Seller agreements support Operator overrides</li><li>Deny Refund Reasons are configured</li><li>Evidence requirements are documented</li><li>Operator denial eligibility is understood</li><li>Denial reversal permissions are restricted</li><li>Damaged, incorrect, lost and change-of-mind rules are defined</li><li>Partial-refund approval rules are documented</li><li>Mixed outcomes are tested</li><li>Customer and Seller templates are ready</li><li>External payments are reconciled before finalisation</li><li>Remittance effects are reviewed after overrides</li><li>Repeated disputes feed into Seller performance management</li></ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/13278067225741-Action-a-refund-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Action a refund as a Seller</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/13278182781837-Action-a-return-as-a-seller\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Action a return as a Seller</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24104906898061-Decline-a-return\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Decline a return</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24105463369101-Approve-a-return\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Approve a return</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/28925785268365-Operator-user-role-permissions\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Operator user role permissions</a></li><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/refunds/howto_advancedrefund/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to use the refunds flow</a></li></ul>"},"related":[["return-workflow","Return Workflow"],["refund-statuses","Refund Statuses"],["refund-financial-adjustments","Refund Financial Adjustments"],["order-exceptions","Order Exceptions"],["refund-integrations","Refund Integrations"]]},"refund-integrations":{"summary":"Connect customer requests, Seller systems, Marketplacer and the payment gateway without creating duplicate refunds, losing workflow ownership or treating a platform status as proof that money has moved.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Customer service","Finance","Technology","Integration partners","Seller management"],"sections":{"Choose the Integration Model":"<p>A refund integration can automate one part of the process or the complete journey.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Automated</th><th>Manual</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Manual</strong></td><td>Nothing</td><td>Request, workflow, finalisation and payment</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Request creation</strong></td><td>Request enters Marketplacer</td><td>Seller decision, financial review and payment</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Workflow synchronisation</strong></td><td>Requests, decisions and statuses</td><td>Financial finalisation or payment, depending on design</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Payment automation</strong></td><td>Approved refund triggers customer payment</td><td>Request and return workflow may remain in Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Fully orchestrated</strong></td><td>Request, workflow, payment and status updates</td><td>Exception handling and reconciliation</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout decision\"><strong>Automation should remove duplicate data entry, not remove control.</strong> The Operator must still identify approval, amount, payment success and Seller remittance effect.</div>","Define System Ownership":"<p>Nominate one authoritative system for each action.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Action</th><th>Possible source of truth</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer request</td><td>Storefront, returns portal or customer service platform</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplace refund workflow</td><td>Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td>Seller decision</td><td>Seller Portal, Shopify or Seller system</td></tr><tr><td>Financial approval</td><td>Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td>Customer funds</td><td>Payment gateway or storefront payment platform</td></tr><tr><td>Customer status updates</td><td>Storefront or customer service platform</td></tr><tr><td>Seller remittance</td><td>Marketplacer</td></tr><tr><td>Finance reconciliation</td><td>Finance or accounting platform</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Define the trigger for each transition and prevent several systems from independently creating or approving the same refund.</p>","Manual Processing":"<p>Use the manual model for low volume, close review, an unavailable payment API, pre-launch fallback or automation failure.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Request received</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Refund Request created</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Workflow completed in Marketplacer</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">4</span><div><strong>Operator marks Refunded</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">5</span><div><strong>Finance refunds payment</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">6</span><div><strong>References reconciled</strong></div></div></div>\n<p>The runbook should name request, monitoring, approval, payment, communication and reconciliation owners. Retain the payment refund reference.</p>","Payment Gateway Integration":"<p>Marketplacer manages the workflow, Invoice Amendment and Seller remittance. The payment gateway returns the customer's money.</p>\n<p>Trigger the payment only after the approved amount is known. Store the Marketplacer Refund Request ID, Seller Invoice ID, Order reference, payment transaction ID, payment refund ID, amount, currency, timestamps, status, errors and retry history.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Payment status</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Not initiated</td><td>No request sent</td></tr><tr><td>Pending</td><td>Gateway accepted but has not completed</td></tr><tr><td>Succeeded</td><td>Funds were refunded successfully</td></tr><tr><td>Failed</td><td>Gateway rejected or failed the request</td></tr><tr><td>Requires review</td><td>Outcome is uncertain</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Do not map Marketplacer Refunded directly to Payment Succeeded.</strong> Confirm the gateway response.</div>","Shopify Plus Operator Integration":"<p>In the standard Shopify Plus Operator pattern, the Refund Request is initiated and approved in Marketplacer. After Operator approval, the integration notifies Shopify Plus and creates the shopper refund.</p>\n<div class=\"process-flow\"><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">1</span><div><strong>Marketplacer workflow completed</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">2</span><div><strong>Integration notifies Shopify Plus</strong></div></div><div class=\"process-step\"><span class=\"step-number\">3</span><div><strong>Shopify creates customer refund</strong></div></div></div>\n<p>Marketplacer owns return approval and Seller financial adjustments. Shopify owns the customer payment transaction. Monitor failures between Marketplacer approval and Shopify payment completion.</p>\n<p>Pre-dispatch cancellations leave applicable Shopify items unfulfilled. Post-dispatch returns leave them fulfilled. Reconcile at Seller Invoice and Line Item level, especially when the Shopify Order also contains first-party items.</p>","MConnect Seller Refund Workflows":"<p>MConnect can support several Shopify Seller refund directions. Confirm feature availability and test the exact Seller configuration before relying on them.</p>\n<h3>Shopify to Marketplacer cancellation sync</h3><p>A Seller cancellation in Shopify can create a Marketplacer Refund Request through MConnect. The Operator still completes the Marketplacer workflow, and the final Refunded or Denied outcome can be written back to Shopify.</p>\n<h3>Marketplacer to Shopify completed-refund sync</h3><p>MConnect can send new Marketplacer cancellations and returns to Shopify after they reach Refunded. Complete, partial Line Item and partial quantity cancellations are supported. Custom added refund items are not supported by this sync.</p>\n<h3>Marketplacer to Shopify return-workflow sync</h3><p>Selected Operators can send Marketplacer return workflows to Shopify for Seller action. Confirm advanced refund requirements, starting-state limitations, Shopify scopes, partial-quantity behaviour and unsupported reopen actions.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Do not enable the workflow without testing partial acceptance and inventory restocking.</strong> Shopify and Marketplacer do not treat every return action identically.</div>","Create Refund Requests by API":"<p>Use <code>refundRequestCreate</code> for cancellations and post-dispatch requests.</p>\n<p>Provide the correct Marketplacer Invoice ID, Line Item ID, quantity, reason, starting status and notes.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Creation status</th><th>Use</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>REFUND_ACCEPTED</code></td><td>No Seller decision or physical return is required</td><td>Can progress toward Operator finalisation</td></tr><tr><td><code>PENDING_APPROVAL</code></td><td>Seller must decide</td><td>Begins Awaiting</td></tr><tr><td><code>AWAITING_RETURN</code></td><td>Physical return is already required</td><td>Seller must assess the returned item</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Choose the starting state from the approved process rather than defaulting every request to the same value.</p>","Automate Cancellations":"<ol><li>Confirm the quantity is undispatched.</li><li>Identify the correct Seller Invoice and Line Item.</li><li>Check for an existing Refund Request.</li><li>Call <code>refundRequestCreate</code> with <code>REFUND_ACCEPTED</code>.</li><li>Store the returned request and Line Item IDs.</li><li>Notify the Operator or continue the approved finalisation flow.</li><li>Coordinate the customer payment refund.</li></ol>\n<p>For a partial cancellation, send only the outstanding quantity. Do not cancel dispatched units.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Using PENDING_APPROVAL for a standard cancellation introduces an unnecessary Seller decision.</strong></div>","Automate Post-Dispatch Returns":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>API action</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>refundRequestCreate</code></td><td>Create the request</td></tr><tr><td><code>refundRequestLineItemReturn</code></td><td>Require a physical return</td></tr><tr><td><code>returnShipmentCreate</code></td><td>Record return Shipment and tracking</td></tr><tr><td><code>refundRequestLineItemAccept</code></td><td>Accept a returnless request or returned item</td></tr><tr><td><code>refundRequestLineItemDeny</code></td><td>Deny the applicable Line Item</td></tr><tr><td><code>refundRequestRefund</code></td><td>Finalise the request</td></tr><tr><td><code>refundRequestApprove</code></td><td>Finalise with granular values where enabled</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Store both the original Invoice Line Item ID and the Refund Request Line Item ID. Later return, accept and deny actions require the latter.</p>","Finalise Refunds by API":"<p>Use <code>refundRequestRefund</code> when Seller-facing steps are complete and the request is ready for Operator finalisation. Accepted items move to Refunded and the Invoice Amendment is created.</p>\n<p><code>refundRequestApprove</code> supports separate customer, commission, remittance and tax values where the capability is enabled. Confirm availability before designing around it.</p>\n<p>The finalisation call completes the Marketplacer record. The integration must still execute and verify the customer payment, store the response, prevent duplicate attempts and reconcile the amount.</p>","Use Webhooks for Status Updates":"<p>Use Marketplacer webhooks to notify connected systems when <strong>RefundRequest</strong>, <strong>RefundRequestLineItem</strong> or <strong>ReturnShipment</strong> changes.</p>\n<p>Operator webhooks are managed under <strong>Configuration → Webhooks</strong>.</p>\n<p>Subscribe only to required events, validate the request, store the event identifier and process idempotently. Marketplacer retries eligible network errors, timeouts, HTTP 5xx responses and HTTP 429 responses.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Treat a webhook as a notification that something changed, not as permission to issue an unverified payment.</strong></div>","Map Statuses Between Systems":"<p>Track each dimension separately.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\"><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Example statuses</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Customer case</td><td>Open, Eligible, Waiting, Resolved</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplacer Refund Request</td><td>Awaiting, Processed, Refunded, Denied</td></tr><tr><td>Marketplacer Line Item</td><td>Pending Approval, Awaiting Return, Refund Accepted, Refunded, Denied</td></tr><tr><td>Physical return</td><td>Not required, Label issued, In transit, Delivered, Assessed</td></tr><tr><td>Payment refund</td><td>Not initiated, Pending, Succeeded, Failed</td></tr><tr><td>Seller remittance</td><td>Not adjusted, Amendment created, Pending recovery, Recovered</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p>Map Processed to <strong>Approved, awaiting financial finalisation</strong>, not customer refunded. Map Refunded to <strong>Marketplacer completed</strong>, then confirm payment separately.</p>\n<p>Store request-level and Line Item-level outcomes because a Refunded request can still contain Denied items.</p>","Prevent Duplicate Refunds":"<p>Before creating a request, check Seller Invoice ID, Line Item ID, quantity, existing Refund Requests, previous Invoice Amendments, customer case reference, external refund reference and dispatch state.</p>\n<p>Maintain a correlation record containing external case ID, Marketplacer request and Line Item IDs, Seller Invoice ID, payment transaction and refund IDs, workflow status and payment status.</p>\n<p>Make request creation, webhook handling and payment execution idempotent. An unknown payment result is not the same as a failed payment. Query the provider before retrying.</p>","Handle Integration Failures":"<h3>Request creation fails</h3><p>Retain the customer case and API error, correct the inputs and query for an existing request before retrying.</p>\n<h3>Webhook delivery fails</h3><p>Review the event response history, destination availability and HTTP status, then reconcile the current object state.</p>\n<h3>Marketplacer is Refunded but payment failed</h3><p>Do not create another Refund Request. Resolve the existing payment and retain the successful reference.</p>\n<h3>Payment succeeded but Marketplacer finalisation failed</h3><p>Do not pay again. Complete the existing Marketplacer record and reconcile the Invoice Amendment and remittance.</p>\n<h3>Storefront and Marketplacer disagree</h3><p>Review external IDs, webhook history, API logs, current status, payment status, partial quantity mapping and unsupported custom items.</p>","Secure the Integration":"<p>Use least-privilege credentials, separate Production and Sandbox and restrict refund approval to systems that genuinely require it.</p>\n<p>For webhooks, use HTTPS, validate a header token or Operator HMAC, rotate secrets, reject invalid requests and retain sufficient audit information.</p>\n<p>Marketplacer webhook source IP addresses are not static, so do not rely on IP allowlisting as the only control.</p>","Reconcile the Complete Refund":"<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><div class=\"structure-node\">Customer case</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Storefront or returns platform</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Marketplacer Refund Request</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Invoice Amendment</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Payment gateway refund</div><div class=\"structure-arrow\">↕</div><div class=\"structure-node\">Seller remittance</div></div>\n<p>Run scheduled reconciliation across Refunded requests, successful payment refunds, amounts and currencies, Invoice Amendments, Remittance to Reclaim, partial and denied Line Items, failures and aged Awaiting or Processed requests.</p>\n<p>Create exception queues for Seller action, Processed finalisation, payment failures, missing amendments, duplicate requests, MConnect failures and negative Seller balances.</p>","Test the Integration":"<h3>Manual fallback</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Create, finalise and pay a refund manually</li><li>Retain payment reference and reconcile amendment</li></ul>\n<h3>API creation and Seller workflow</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>REFUND_ACCEPTED cancellation</li><li>PENDING_APPROVAL return</li><li>AWAITING_RETURN request</li><li>Partial quantity and invalid quantity</li><li>Duplicate request attempt</li><li>Seller returnless, return-required and denial paths</li></ul>\n<h3>Finalisation, webhooks and payment</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Invoice Amendment values are correct</li><li>Payment executes once</li><li>Repeated events are idempotent</li><li>Timeout, pending and failed payment states are handled</li><li>Out-of-order webhooks do not overwrite current state</li></ul>\n<h3>Shopify or MConnect</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li>Supported cancellation and return directions</li><li>Partial quantity and custom-item limitations</li><li>Inventory restocking behaviour</li><li>Refunded and Denied outcomes synchronise</li></ul>","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\"><li>The integration model and system ownership are documented</li><li>Request, approval and payment responsibilities are separate</li><li>Manual fallback is ready</li><li>Marketplacer and payment statuses are stored separately</li><li>API creation states are mapped correctly</li><li>Mixed Line Item outcomes are supported</li><li>Payment execution is idempotent</li><li>Duplicate requests are prevented</li><li>Webhook authentication, retries and duplicate handling are tested</li><li>Production and Sandbox credentials are separate</li><li>Finance can reconcile payments, amendments and remittance</li><li>MConnect availability and limitations are confirmed</li><li>Failure scenarios have owners</li><li>Customer and Seller communications reflect actual status</li></ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3><ul class=\"check-list\"><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/refunds/howto_advancedrefund/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to use the refunds flow</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/28414815410445-Shopify-Plus-How-data-is-synchronized\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Shopify Plus: How data is synchronized</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/37900196948109-Enable-cancellation-sync-from-Shopify-to-Marketplacer\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Enable cancellation sync from Shopify to Marketplacer</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/37258639804173-Enable-cancellation-sync-from-Marketplacer-to-Shopify\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Enable cancellation sync from Marketplacer to Shopify</a></li><li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/38916842988301-Enable-return-flow-sync-from-Marketplacer-to-Shopify\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Enable return flow sync from Marketplacer to Shopify</a></li><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/webhooksgettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Getting Started with Webhooks</a></li><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/webhookretries/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhook Retry Policy</a></li><li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/securingwebhooks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Securing Webhooks</a></li></ul>"},"related":[["refund-foundations","Refund Foundations"],["refund-statuses","Refund Statuses"],["refund-financial-adjustments","Refund Financial Adjustments"],["refund-disputes","Refund Disputes and Exceptions"],["integration-architecture","Integration Architecture"]]}};
